Rating: 3
Folks, I'm surprised that so many cooks are looking up -- and reviewing -- such a banal recipe as that for a potato salad, something I thought we could all dream up with our eyes closed. I'm guilty myself, obviously, although I've been making my German mother's version - sans recipe - for 20 years. The trick to any good potato salad is saturating the potatoes with vinegar while they're warm (use a much more liberal dose than this recipe calls for), as one reviewer noted. A good German cook does this two days before even deigning to serve the salad, allowing the vinegar and salt and pepper to fully penetrate the potatoes. The only other things I'd alter in this recipe are, yes, stepping up the garlic and chopping the celery very fine. Use petite frozen peas (if you haven't got fresh), too. And, naturally, it would be better if you made fresh aioli from scratch, with organic/free range eggs! This really is good, just trust your judgment - no one really needs a recipe for potato salad!

